Rapid Control Prototyping

Description

Rapid Control Prototyping (RCP) enables you to test and verify your control designs using real motors and hardware prototypes prior to selecting the final controller hardware. This offers you great flexibility in early development stages, as you are not constrained by the limited computing resources and IO connectivity options, typically offered by embedded controllers. Furthermore, you can perform fast iterations between desktop simulation and design tasks (like the ones offered in MIL section) and real-time simulation and testing on hardware. All in all, RCP allows you to detect design flaws earlier in the development process, expediting the development and time-to-market of your embedded controller.
Speedgoat real-time target machines acting as prototype motor controllers, allied to Simulink Real-Time, provide you the quickest possible path from MATLAB & Simulink desktop simulation to real-time testing with hardware: autogenerate and download a real-time application from Simulink at the click of a button, connect I/O with your hardware, and get started right away with on the fly testing and tuning of motor controls (watch workflow video).

Learn how to

  • Deploy and run motor control algorithms in real-time: from scalar control (open-loop) to automatically tuning a field-oriented control algorithm
  • Tune parameters on-the-fly, and estimate motor parameters and calibrate sensor with just a few steps
  • Prototype your controller on Speedgoat target hardware and quickly spin a brushless DC motor using Simulink Real-Time and the Speedgoat Electric Motor Control Kit
  • Achieve closed-loop sample rates up to the MHz range, and PWM generation and capture time resolution support as low as 5ns
